# Deploying Your Backend to Railway

**Where do environment variables go (Vercel vs Railway)?** See **[docs/deployment/ENV_VARS_VERCEL_AND_RAILWAY.md](docs/deployment/ENV_VARS_VERCEL_AND_RAILWAY.md)** — full table for every group of vars.

Your code changes are done. Now follow these steps in your browser.

## What counts as the “API service” on Railway?

If you see **one** card (e.g. **SoloSuccess AI**), **that card is your API service**. Open it → **Variables** is where backend env vars go. You do **not** need a second card unless you added something extra (e.g. a separate Postgres plugin).

## Step 1 — Push your latest code

Push to **your** Git remote (this project may use **Gitea**, not GitHub). Railway only rebuilds from whatever source **you** connected (connected Git provider, mirror repo, Docker image, or CLI deploy).

## How this repo connects to Railway (important)

**Optional — wired in CI:** If you add the four Railway secrets documented in [`.gitea/README.md`](.gitea/README.md), [`.gitea/workflows/deploy.yaml`](.gitea/workflows/deploy.yaml) runs `railway up server --ci --path-as-root` after each successful **main** branch deploy to Vercel. If those secrets are **not** set, the workflow skips Railway (no error).

Otherwise the codebase still does not record whether you use a **Git mirror**, **manual CLI**, or **registry** — that is whatever you configured in the Railway dashboard. Do **not** use both Railway’s Git auto-deploy **and** the Gitea `railway up` step on the same service (double deploys).

So **only your Railway dashboard** (or your memory of setup) tells the truth. On [railway.app](https://railway.app) open the **SoloSuccess AI** service → **Settings**:

| What you see | Likely method |
|----------------|---------------|
| **Connected repo** (GitHub / GitLab) with your app name | Git integration — if code “really” lives on Gitea, that is often a **mirror** or second remote of the same repo. |
| **Docker image** URL (e.g. GHCR, Docker Hub) | **Registry** deploy. |
| **Empty / template** and you deploy from your PC | Often **Railway CLI** (`railway link` + `railway up`) or manual image push. |

**Deployments** tab: each deploy usually shows the trigger (Git commit, CLI, image digest).

## Step 2 — Log into Railway

Go to [railway.app](https://railway.app) and log in.

## Step 3 — Service already there vs new project

**If the service already exists** (one **SoloSuccess AI** card): open it → **Settings** → confirm **Root Directory** is **`server`** (or your deploy uses `server/Dockerfile`). You can skip “create project” steps.

**If you are creating from scratch:**

1. **New Project** → connect a repository Railway supports **or** use **Empty Project** / **Docker** / **Railway CLI** if your code lives only on Gitea (Railway’s built-in picker is often GitHub/GitLab; Gitea-only flows commonly use a **mirror**, **CLI**, or **container registry**).
2. Set **Root Directory** to **`server`** when the repo is this monorepo.
3. Deploy — Railway should use `server/Dockerfile` when present.

## Step 4 — Add Environment Variables in Railway
Once deployed, click on your service → **"Variables"** tab → add each one:

| Variable | Value |
|---|---|
| `NODE_ENV` | `production` |
| `DATABASE_URL` | *(copy from `server/.env`)* |
| `JWT_SECRET` | *(make a strong random string — use [randomkeygen.com](https://randomkeygen.com))* |
| `CLIENT_URL` | `https://solosuccessai.fun` |
| `GEMINI_API_KEY` | *(copy from `server/.env`)* |
| `UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL` | *(copy from `server/.env`)* |
| `UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN` | *(copy from `server/.env`)* |
| `SENTRY_DSN` | *(optional — from your [Sentry](https://sentry.io) project → DSN)* |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The `JWT_SECRET` you set in Railway **must also be set in Vercel** with the same value. Both sides need to match.

## Step 5 — Get Your Railway URL
After deploy completes, go to **"Settings"** → **"Domains"** → copy the URL (looks like `https://solosuccess-api.up.railway.app`).

Test it: open `https://your-railway-url/api/health` in your browser — you should see `{"status":"ok","websocket":"active",...}`.

## Step 6 — Add Variables in Vercel
Go to your Vercel project → **Settings** → **Environment Variables** → add:

| Variable | Value |
|---|---|
| `NEXT_PUBLIC_SOCKET_URL` | Your Railway URL from Step 5 |
| `JWT_SECRET` | Same value you set in Railway |

Then click **Redeploy** in Vercel.

## That's It! ✅
Real-time notifications will now work. When a user gets a new notification, a toast will appear instantly without needing to refresh.
